text: Blue Ivy north and Apple these names of
celebrity offsprings sparked interest
around the world and they beg the
question does anything go when it comes
to naming your child with the arrival of
another royal baby in the UK we took a
look at baby naming rules what you can
and cannot legally call your child
depends on where in the world it's born
in Germany for example there are several
naming guidelines which are enforced by
local registry offices these say a child
must not be given a name which does not
conform to their sex any name must also
be a recognizable first name which means
that surnames compañía prior names as
well as football teams are generally not
permissible the point is to protect the
welfare of the child and to prevent
ridicule disagreements between parents
and registers can be settled in court
German judges have ruled against names
such as Borussia after the football team
Lourdes and peppermint peppermint but in
favor of names such as Kozma Shiva and
galaxy nough in the u.s. things are a
little more relaxed it's up to each
state to set the baby naming rules and
some Germans look away now
don't have any rules at all this means
in states like Arkansas test and unknown
you could make it on to the birth
certificate though even these children
may count themselves lucky given that in
Michigan parents don't have to name
their child at all in New Mexico and
Texas parents are banned from formally
calling their child and obscenity some
are out other states like California Ben
uncontroversial names if they have
hyphens or accents such as Nicholas or
Rene in Iceland things are even more
restrictive parents unless their foreign
nationals must choose their child's name
from a list of around 3,600 pre-approved
Icelandic names acceptable examples
include Bergen or an ace builder if
Icelandic parents have an alternative
name in mind a committee will determine
if it's allowable by law meanwhile in
China parents are advised to choose
Dru's that are computer readable when
naming their child likewise in Japan
parents should choose their child's name
from a list of commonly used kanji
characters or names the UK is deemed to
be among the more flexible countries in
terms of baby naming rules here are a
few examples of the uncommon names given
in 2017 short of offensive words or
numerals there are few restrictions to
naming the newest addition to the royal
family
